  "prompt": "Who designed mint.com?",
  "response": "Mint.com was founded and initially designed by Aaron Patzer in 2006. As the creator and CEO, Patzer developed Mint.com as a personal finance management tool aimed at helping users track their expenses, create budgets, and manage their financial goals seamlessly. The platform integrated various financial accounts, allowing users to view all their financial information in one centralized location.\n\nUnder Patzer's leadership, Mint.com experienced rapid growth due to its user-friendly interface and effective financial tracking features. In 2009, just three years after its launch, Intuit, the maker of popular financial software like TurboTax and QuickBooks, acquired Mint.com for approximately $170 million. Since the acquisition, Mint.com has continued to operate as a subsidiary of Intuit, maintaining its focus on personal finance management tools.\n\nWhile Aaron Patzer was the primary visionary behind Mint.com, the success of the platform was also supported by a dedicated team of developers, designers, and financial experts who contributed to its development and ongoing enhancements.",
